Clover has very little information about allergens available on their website. This would not be so problematic if they had a phone number...but they don't. And their email response says please expect an email response in 1-2 weeks. So if someone with allergies trying to select a restaurant in advance can't really do so safely. I have Celiac disease and went to the Harvard Square location in person to ask if they have food I can eat, in advance of a group order. I had viewed their online menu and noted that everything marked "gluten free" had a fried component. I asked the staff person if there was anything on the lunch menu that someone with Celiac disease could safely eat. They said, "yes, but I need to warn you that there may be some cross-contamination." To me, a general warning about cross-contamination is normal, and usually just indicates that a kitchen also processes gluten. So I asked if their fryer also fries things with gluten. They said yes. This is not "the potential for cross-contamination." This is 100% not safe for people with celiac disease. I understand that many restaurants do not work for people with celiac disease. That is to be expected. However, Clover failed in several additional ways: not having a way for people to determine beforehand if they have food that is safe, and having staff members who provide incorrect (and potentially harmful) information to customers, which shows a lack in understanding and training about allergens
